<section xml:id="section-activity-clo17">
  <title>Activity for CLO-17</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo17-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How can an integral be used to define a new function?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An integral defined a new function by allowing the variable
          of the function to be the upper bound of the integral. In
          this sense, a new function measures the area under the curve
          of a previously known function with a fixed starting point
          and a variable ending point for the area. This is a common
          method of building new functions in mathematics. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is an antiderivative?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An antiderivative of a function <m>f(x)</m> is some function
          <m>g(x)</m> such that <m>g^\prime(x) = f(x)</m>. It is
          essentially doing differentiation backwards: an
          antiderivative wants to know what function has a specific
          already stated derivative. The derivative is known but the
          original function is unknown. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are definite and indefinite integrals?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A definite integral is a measurenent of an area under a
          curve. It is defined by the Riemann integral, a limit of
          approximation by rectangles. It has bounds on the integral
          sign to indicate the interval of integration. The result of
          a definite integral is a number
        </p>
        <p>
          An indefinite integral is a notation for an antiderivative.
          It takes a function and produces the antiderivative for that
          function (which will always involve an unknown constant of
          integration). It has no bounds on the integral sign, since
          there is not specific interval or area being considered. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the main idea of the fundamental theorm of calculus. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The main idea is that integrals are an inverse process to
          derivatives. To do an integral, we can essentially just do a
          derivative backwards. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How you calculate a definite integral?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          You find an antiderivative for the function. Then you
          evaluate the antiderivative on the upper bound, evaluate the
          antiderivative on the lower bound, and take the difference
          of these two values. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why is the fundamental theorem of calculus so important?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For two main reasons. First, it is a deep conceptual
          connection between the two main definitions: derivative and
          integrals. It is a realization that these are just two sides
          of the same coin. They are the same process, just one
          forward and one in reverse. 
        </p>
        <p>
          More practically, the fundamental theorem is a way to
          calculate integrals. Rules for differentiation can be
          calculated from the definition. The definition of a
          derivative is, relatively speaking, an easy definition to
          work with. The definition of the integral, however, is a
          very troublesome definition. It's very difficult to work
          with and difficult to use to make rules and calculation
          methods. The fundamental theorem means that we can use all
          that we know about derivative, just in reverse. Now, in
          reverse is harder than regular derivative, but it much
          easier and much more approachable than trying to
          understand integrals just from the definition. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-fundamental-theorem">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Fundamental Theorem</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          <md>
            \int -\sin x dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I look to the tables of derivatives. <m>-\sin x</m> shows up
          as the derivative of <m>\cos x</m>, so I go backwards to
          that original function.
          <md>
            \int -\sin x dx = \cos x + c 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          <md>
            \int \frac{1}{x} dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I look to the tables of derivatives. If I differentiate
          <m>\ln x</m>, I get <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>, so I go backwards
          to that original function.
          <md>
            \int \frac{1}{x} dx = \ln x + c 
          </md>
          If I look at the tables of integrals, I can actually do a
          bit better than this. The right side of the above equation
          is only defined for <m>x > 0</m>, but the left side is
          defined for all <m>x \neq 0</m>. There is an antiderivative
          that matches the full domain. 
          <md>
            \int \frac{1}{x} dx = \ln |x| + c 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards. You can
          use the linearity of the integral.
          <md>
            \int (4 \cos x + 6 \sin x) dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can use linearity to split this into two integrals. 
          <md>
            \int (4 \cos x + 6 \sin x) dx = 4 \int \cos x dx + 6 \int
            \sin x dx 
          </md>
          Then I look at the derivative tables and work backwards to
          get the antiderivatives of sine and cosine. 
          <md>
            = 4 \int \cos x dx + 6 \int \sin x dx = 4 \sin x - 6 \cos
            x + c 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards. You can
          use the linearity of the integral. 
          <md>
            \int (x^3-e^x)dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can use linearity to split this into two integrals.
          <md>
            \int (x^3-e^x)dx = \int x^3 dx - \int e^x dx 
          </md>
          For the first integral, I have to do the power rule
          backwards. This increases the exponent and divides by the
          new exponent. For the second integral, since the exponential
          function is its own derivative, it is also its own
          antiderivative. 
          <md>
            \int x^3 dx - \int e^x dx = \frac{x^4}{4} - e^x + c 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          However, don't do the chain rule backwards; instead, use
          what you know about the chain rule to make a reasonable
          guess for the antiderivative.
          <md>
            \int e^{4x} dx
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If I were to differentiate this, it would be a chain rule
          derivative. The outside function would remain unchanged, but
          the inside derivative is <m>\frac{d}{dx} 4x = 4</m>, so I
          would have to multiply by 4. Going backwards, then, I
          should do the opposite and divide by 4. 
          <md>
            \int e^{4x} dx = \frac{1}{4} e^{4x} + c 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          <md>
            \int_0^{\pi} \sin x dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The antiderivative of <m>\sin x</m> is <m>(-\cos x)</m>. For
          definite integrals, after I find the antiderivative, I
          evaluate it on the bounds. (I don't need the constant of
          integral in definite integrals, since it would just cancel
          off when I evaluate on the bounds.)
          <md>
            \int_0^{\pi} \sin x dx = -\cos x \Big|_0^{\pi} = -\cos
            (\pi) - (- \cos (0)) = -(-1) - (-1) = 2
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          <md>
            \int_1^{\ln 4} e^x dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The antiderivative of the exponential it itself. I need to
          evaluate on the bounds. Remember that the logarithm and the
          exponential are inverse operations, so they remove each
          other. 
          <md>
            \int_1^{\ln 4} e^x dx = e^x \Big|_1^{\ln 4} = e^{\ln 4} -
            e^{1} = 4 - e
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the following antiderivative by using known
          derivatives or doing the derivative rules backwards.
          <md>
            \int_1^5 (2x-7) dx 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I use linearity to split up the integral.
          <md>
            \int_1^5 (2x-7) dx = \int_1^5 2x dx - \int_1^5 7 dx
          </md>
          Then I use the power rule backwards for the first integral.
          In the second, the antiderivative of a constant is just the
          variable itself. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_1^5 2x dx - \int_1^5 7 dx \amp = \frac{2x^2}{2}
              \Big|_1^5 - 7x \Big|_1^5 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 5^2 - 1^2 - (7(5) - 7) = 25 - 1 - 35 + 7 = -4 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
